    <id>http://weblog.savanne.be/150-career-advice</id>
    <link href="http://weblog.savanne.be/150-career-advice" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/>
    <title>Career advice</title>
    <summary type="xhtml"><div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">If all goes well, I should be getting my Master in Computer Science diploma next July.  This means I've been keeping my eyes open for interesting job opportunities the last few months, especially the last two days, when I was at <a href="http://www.devoxx.com/">Devoxx</a>.<br/>
<br/>
From this small survey, I've noticed a few things:<br/>
<br/>
<ul><br/>
<li>Most jobs available are of the consultant kind: either it's installing and configuring existing software, or developing custom business software for specific companies. Or it implies architecting solutions composing of these existing pieces of software, without writing a single line of code.</li>
<li>Open source jobs usually imply working from home, which unfortunately also means no direct face-to-face colleagues. Something which doesn't look too appealing at this point in my life.</li>
<li>Also, I often have the feeling that they are coding-jobs for life. I love programming now (that is actually an understatement), but I'm not sure if I'd like to do it forever, having some possible carreer path would be nice.</li>
<li>If you like to work on product software (as opposed to custom business software), most of the action is going on in the US (Google, IBM, Sun and most big Linux companies), the UK (Canonical) or Germany (part of Novell) [1].</li>
</ul><br/>
<br/>
This basically leaves me wondering:<br/>
<br/>
What kind of jobs are there:<br/>
<ul><br/>
<li>That involve projects that are useable in more than one installation, this doesn't have to be open [2], but it would be nice if it were a product, rather than a one-off custom brew.</li>
<li>That allow me to stay in Belgium. I have very good personal reasons to stay in this country, for now.</li>
<li>In which I have face-to-face colleagues. I do not like running a one man office where I can 't meet new people.</li>
</ul><br/>
<br/>
Are my fears correct in the sense that finding a job like this will be quite impossible here in Belgium? Or are my impressions totally wrong? Comments welcome, as I have increasingly less of an idea what I want to do when I graduate.<br/>
<br/>
[1] <em>This might not be completely correct, as I'm no expert on the exact locations of all the offices of all these companies.</em><br/>
[2] <em>But off-course, anything that is related to the open-source world is the way of the future, the whole proprietary ecosystem feels so... inefficient.</em></div>
    </summary>
